The paper deals with the problem of identifying a subset of active users in a set of potentially active users over a multiple access channel. This involves the use of physical-layer network coding, K-out-of-N signature coding, and coded slotted ALOHA (CSA) techniques. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory), which deals with the fundamental limits of data communication and storage. The paper also involves the use of network protocols and algorithms, which suggests the sub-categories cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The use of graphs in the proposed algorithm suggests the sub-category cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), which deals with the design and analysis of efficient algorithms and data structures. Finally, the paper involves the analysis of the performance of the proposed algorithm, which suggests the sub-category cs.LG (Machine Learning), which deals with the design and analysis of algorithms that can learn from and make predictions on data.
